property.encoding: Systems and Services Acquisition: (i) Allocate sufficient resources to adequately protect organizational^linebreak$information systems; (ii) employ system development life cycle processes that incorporate information^linebreak$security considerations; (iii) employ software usage and installation restrictions; and (iv) ensure that thirdparty^linebreak$providers employ adequate security measures to protect information, applications, and/or services^linebreak$outsourced from the organization.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Network attack surface: This category refers to vulnerabilities over an enterprise^linebreak$network, wide-area network, or the Internet. Included in this category^linebreak$are network protocol vulnerabilities, such as those used for a denial-of-service^linebreak$attack,^linebreak$disruption of communications links, and various forms of intruder attacks.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Media Protection: (i) Protect information system media, both paper and digital; (ii) limit access to information^linebreak$on information system media to authorized users; and (iii) sanitize or destroy information system media^linebreak$before disposal or release for reuse.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Attack: An assault on system security that derives from ^linebreak$an intelligent threat; that is, an intelligent act that is a deliberate^linebreak$attempt (especially in the sense of a method or ^linebreak$technique) to evade security services and violatethe security^linebreak$policy of a system.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Separation of privilege is defined in [SALT75] as a practice in which multiple^linebreak$privilege attributes are required to achieve access to a restricted resource.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Maintenance: (i) Perform periodic and timely maintenance on organizational information systems; and (ii)^linebreak$provide effective controls on the tools, techniques, mechanisms, and personnel used to conduct information^linebreak$system maintenance.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Isolation is a principle that applies in three contexts. First, public access systems^linebreak$should be isolated from critical resources (data, processes, etc.) to prevent disclosure^linebreak$or tampering.

property.encoding: Psychological acceptability implies that the security mechanisms should not^linebreak$interfere unduly with the work of users, while at the same time meeting the needs^linebreak$of those who authorize access.

property.encoding: Risk: An expectation of loss expressed as the probability ^linebreak$that a particular threat will exploit a particular vulnerability^linebreak$with a particular harmful result.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Interference: A threat action whereby an unauthorized entity^linebreak$indirectly^linebreak$accesses sensitive data (but not necessarily the^linebreak$data contained^linebreak$in the communication) by reasoning from^linebreak$characteristics^linebreak$or by-products of communications.

property.encoding: Risk Assessment: Periodically assess the risk to organizational operations (including mission, functions,^linebreak$image, or reputation), organizational assets, and individuals, resulting from the operation of organizational^linebreak$information systems and the associated processing, storage, or transmission of organizational information.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Vulnerability: A flaw or weakness in a systems design, implementation, ^linebreak$or operation and management that could be^linebreak$exploited to violate the systems security policy.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Contingency Planning: Establish, maintain, and implement plans for emergency response, backup operations,^linebreak$and postdisaster recovery for organizational information systems to ensure the availability of critical^linebreak$information resources and continuity of operations in emergency situations.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: An attack tree is a branching, hierarchical data structure that represents a set of^linebreak$potential techniques for exploiting security vulnerabilities [MAUW05, MOOR01,^linebreak$SCHN99]. The security incident that is the goal of the attack is represented as the^linebreak$root node of the tree, and the ways that an attacker could reach that goal are iteratively^linebreak$and incrementally represented as branches and subnodes of the tree. Each^linebreak$subnode defines a subgoal, and each subgoal may have its own set of further subgoals,^linebreak$etc. The final nodes on the paths outward from the root, i.e., the leaf nodes,^linebreak$represent different ways to initiate an attack.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Awareness and Training: (i) Ensure that managers and users of organizational information systems are made^linebreak$aware of the security risks associated with their activities and of the applicable laws, regulation, and policies^linebreak$related to the security of organizational information systems; and (ii) ensure that personnel are adequately^linebreak$trained to carry out their assigned information security-related duties and responsibilities.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Fail-safe default means that access decisions should be based on permission^linebreak$rather than exclusion.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Topic 1

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Planning: (i) Limit physical access to information systems, equipment, and^linebreak$the respective operating environments to authorized individuals; (ii) protect the physical plant and support^linebreak$infrastructure for information systems; (iii) provide supporting utilities for information systems; (iv) protect^linebreak$information systems against environmental hazards; and (v) provide appropriate environmental controls in^linebreak$facilities containing information systems.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Economy of mechanism means that the design of security measures embodied^linebreak$in both hardware and software should be as simple and small as possible. The^linebreak$motivation for this principle is that relatively simple, small design is easier to test^linebreak$and verify thoroughly.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Misuse: Causes a system component to perform a function or^linebreak$service that is detrimental to system security.

property.encoding: Open design means that the design of a security mechanism should be open^linebreak$rather than secret.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Configuration Management: (i) Establish and maintain baseline configurations and inventories of^linebreak$organizational information systems (including hardware, software, firmware, and documentation)^linebreak$throughout the respective system development life cycles; and (ii) establish and enforce security^linebreak$configuration settings for information technology products employed in organizational information^linebreak$systems.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Software attack surface: This refers to vulnerabilities in application, utility,^linebreak$or operating system code. A particular focus in this category is Web server^linebreak$software.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Threat: A potential for violation of security, which exists when ^linebreak$there is a circumstance, capability, action, or event, that^linebreak$could breach security and cause harm. That is, a threat ^linebreak$is a possible danger that might exploit a vulnerability.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Security Policy: A set of rules and practices that specify or regulate ^linebreak$how a system or organization provides security services to^linebreak$protect sensitive and critical system resources.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Least astonishment means that a program or user interface should always^linebreak$respond in the way that is least likely to astonish the user.

property.encoding: How does it do it

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Identification and Authentication: Identify information system users, processes acting on behalf of users, or^linebreak$devices, and authenticate (or verify) the identities of those users, processes, or devices, as a prerequisite to^linebreak$allowing access to organizational information systems.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Incident Response: (i) Establish an operational incident-handling capability for organizational information^linebreak$systems that includes adequate preparation, detection, analysis, containment, recovery, and user-response^linebreak$activities; and (ii) track, document, and report incidents to appropriate organizational officials and/or^linebreak$authorities.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Physical and Environmental Protection: (i) Limit physical access to information systems, equipment, and^linebreak$the respective operating environments to authorized individuals; (ii) protect the physical plant and support^linebreak$infrastructure for information systems; (iii) provide supporting utilities for information systems; (iv) protect^linebreak$information systems against environmental hazards; and (v) provide appropriate environmental controls in^linebreak$facilities containing information systems.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Repudiation: An entity deceives another by falsely denying^linebreak$responsibility^linebreak$for an act.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Complete mediation means that every access must be checked against the^linebreak$access control mechanism.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Human attack surface: This category refers to vulnerabilities created by personnel^linebreak$or outsiders, such as social engineering, human error, and trusted insiders.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Masquerade: An unauthorized entity gains access to a system or^linebreak$performs a malicious act by posing as an authorized entity.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Corruption: Undesirably alters system operation by adversely^linebreak$modifying system functions or data.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Interception: An unauthorized entity directly accesses sensitive^linebreak$data traveling between authorized sources and destinations.

property.encoding: Personal Security: (i) Ensure that individuals occupying positions of responsibility within organizations^linebreak$(including third-party service providers) are trustworthy and meet established security criteria for those^linebreak$positions; (ii) ensure that organizational information and information systems are protected during and after^linebreak$personnel actions such as terminations and transfers; and (iii) employ formal sanctions for personnel failing to^linebreak$comply with organizational security policies and procedures.

property.encoding: Misappropriation: An entity assumes unauthorized logical or^linebreak$physical control of a system resource.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Intrusion: An unauthorized entity gains access to sensitive data^linebreak$by circumventing a systems security protections.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Exposure: Sensitive data are directly^linebreak$ released to an unauthorized^linebreak$entity.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: System Resource (Asset): Data contained in an information system; ^linebreak$or a service provided by a system; or a system capability, such as^linebreak$processing power or communication bandwidth; or an ^linebreak$item of system equipment (i.e., a system component^linebreak$hardware, firmware, software, or documentation); ^linebreak$or a facility that houses system operations and equipment.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Layering refers to the use of multiple, overlapping protection approaches^linebreak$addressing the people, technology, and operational aspects of information systems.

property.encoding: Least privilege means that every process and every user of the system should^linebreak$operate using the least set of privileges necessary to perform the task.

property.encoding: System and Information Integrity: (i) Identify, report, and correct information and information system flaws^linebreak$in a timely manner; (ii) provide protection from malicious code at appropriate locations within organizational^linebreak$information systems; and (iii) monitor information system security alerts and advisories and take appropriate^linebreak$actions in response.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Access Control: Limit information system access to authorized users, ^linebreak$processes acting on behalf of authorized users, or devices (including ^linebreak$other information systems) and to the types of transactions and functions that^linebreak$authorized users are permitted to exercise.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Adversary: An entity that attacks, or is a threat to, a system.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Encapsulation can be viewed as a specific form of isolation based on objectoriented^linebreak$functionality. Protection is provided by encapsulating a collection of procedures^linebreak$and data objects in a domain of its own so that the internal structure of a^linebreak$data object is accessible only to the procedures of the protected subsystem and the^linebreak$procedures may be called only at designated domain entry points.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: System and Communications Protection: (i) Monitor, control, and protect organizational communications^linebreak$(i.e., information transmitted or received by organizational information systems) at the external boundaries^linebreak$and key internal boundaries of the information systems; and (ii) employ architectural designs, software development^linebreak$techniques, and systems engineering principles that promote effective information security within^linebreak$organizational information systems.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Audit and Accountability: (i) Create, protect, and retain information system audit records to the^linebreak$extent needed to enable the monitoring, analysis, investigation, and reporting of unlawful, unauthorized,^linebreak$or inappropriate information system activity; and (ii) ensure that the actions of individual information^linebreak$system users can be uniquely traced to those users so they can be held accountable for their^linebreak$actions.

property.encoding: Countermeasure: An action, device, procedure, or technique that ^linebreak$reduces a threat, a vulnerability, or an attack by eliminating^linebreak$or preventing it, by minimizing the harm it can cause, or ^linebreak$by discovering and reporting it so that corrective^linebreak$action can be taken.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Certification, Accredation, and Security Assessments: (i) Periodically assess the security controls in^linebreak$organizational information systems to determine if the controls are effective in their application; (ii) develop^linebreak$and implement plans of action designed to correct deficiencies and reduce or eliminate vulnerabilities in^linebreak$organizational information systems; (iii) authorize the operation of organizational information systems and any^linebreak$associated information system connections; and (iv) monitor information system security controls on an^linebreak$ongoing basis to ensure the continued effectiveness of the controls.

property.name: _phrase
property.encoding: Modularity in the context of security refers both to the development of security^linebreak$functions as separate, protected modules and to the use of a modular architecture^linebreak$for mechanism design and implementation.

property.encoding: Obstruction: A threat action that interrupts delivery of system^linebreak$services by hindering system operation.
